      <title>Mysterious 'ghost ship' found off the coast of Myanmar</title>
      <description><![CDATA[For story suggestions or custom animation requests, contact tips@nextanimation.com.tw. Visit http://archive.nextanimationstudio.com to view News Direct's complete archive of 3D news animations.RESTRICTIONS: Broadcast: NO USE JAPAN, NO USE TAIWAN Digital: NO USE JAPAN, NO USE TAIWANOfficials are investigating a ship that was found drifting off the coast of Myanmar, reports Fox News.The "ghost ship" was discovered by fishermen about 11 kilometers off the coast off Yangon, Myanmar.Officials say the empty cargo ship, named Sam Rataulangi PB 1600, was being towed by a tugboat, called Independence, to a ship-breaking factory in Bangladesh.In a Facebook post, the Yangon police said the ship had an Indonesian flag. The vessel was also reported to be more than 177 meters long, according to the Marine Traffic website.According to AFP, the bad weather caused the cables attached to the ship broke as the ship neared the Yangon River. This is when the crew decided to abandon the ship.Myanmar Navy officials decided to use coastal radar records to track down the approximate location of the two vessels, Fox News reports.Officials involved in the case are still investigating further, as the ship's last recorded location was reportedly off the coast of Taiwan before appearing in Myanmar waters.RUNDOWN SHOWS:1. An empty cargo ship is shown being towed in the sea to Bangladesh2. The design of the ship, with the Indonesian flag, is shown here, along with its size.3. The cables attached to the cargo ship and tugboat break apart, and the ship has being stranded.4. The coastal radar being used to find the approximate location of the two vessels.VOICEOVER (in English): "Officials say the empty cargo ship was being towed by a tugboat to a ship-breaking factory in Bangladesh.""In a Facebook post, the Yangon police said the ship had an Indonesian flag. According to the Marine Traffic website, the vessel was also reported to be more than 177 meters long.""According to AFP, bad weather caused the cables attached to the ship to break as the ship neared the Yangon River. This is when the crew decided to abandon the ship.""Fox News reports Myanmar Navy officials decided to use coastal radar records to track down the approximate location of the two vessels."SOURCES: Fox News, France 24, Marine Traffic, Sky News, Eleven Myanmar, Myanmar Times, The BBC, http://www.foxnews.com/world/2018/09/02/ghost-ship-found-drifting-off-coast-burma-navy-solves-mystery.htmlhttps://www.france24.com/en/20180901-ghost-ship-myanmar-waters-earlier-towed-indonesian-manned-vessel-navyhttps://www.marinetraffic.com/en/ais/details/ships/shipid:702959/mmsi:525003026/imo:9151981/vessel:SAM_RATULANGI_PB_1600https://news.sky.com/story/mystery-of-myanmar-ghost-ship-solved-11487693http://www.elevenmyanmar.com/local/14847https://www.mmtimes.com/news/ghost-ship-runs-aground-thongwa.htmlhttps://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-45377707***]]></description>
