      <title>What causes 'black hair' on your tongue?</title>
      <description><![CDATA[For story suggestions or custom animation requests, contact tips@nextanimation.com.tw. Visit http://archive.nextanimationstudio.com to view News Direct's complete archive of 3D news animations.RESTRICTIONS: Broadcast: NO USE JAPAN, NO USE TAIWAN Digital: NO USE JAPAN, NO USE TAIWANA 55-year-old woman developed a case of black hairy tongue after taking an antibiotic for an infected wound.The case was published by Dr. Yasir Hamad, an assistant professor in the Department of Medicine at the Washington University School of Medicine in St. Louis, in the New England Journal of Medicine on Wednesday, according to CNN. The condition refers to when papillae on the tongue grow longer than normal and turn black. Papillae are normally less than a millimeter long, but can grow to between 12 and 18 millimeters in length in patients suffering from the condition. The blackening occurs as the growing papillae trap microscopic food particles that allow bacteria and other microbes to flourish on the tongue. Black hairy tongue is an uncommon and harmless side effect of some drugs, but can also be caused by smoking, bad oral hygiene and some medical conditions. In this case, the woman was taking minocycline to treat a wound infection from a car accident. Within a week, her tongue turned black, she started feeling nauseous and developed a foul taste in her mouth. Four weeks after doctors changed her medication, her tongue turned back to its normal color.    RUNDOWN SHOWS:1. Woman developing black hairy tongue after taking antibiotic2. Normal papillae growing and turning black3. Blackening occurring from trapped food particles and other causes of the condition4. Woman's tongue turning back to normal colorVOICEOVER (in English): "A 55-year-old woman developed a case of black hairy tongue after taking an antibiotic for an infected wound. The condition refers to when papillae on the tongue grow longer than normal and turn black." "Papillae are normally less than a millimeter long, but can grow to between 12 and 18 millimeters in length in patients suffering from the condition." "The blackening occurs as the growing papillae trap microscopic food particles that allow bacteria and other microbes to flourish on the tongue. It is an uncommon and harmless side effect of some drugs, but can also be caused by smoking, bad oral hygiene and some medical conditions." "In this case, four weeks after doctors changed the woman's medication, her tongue turned back to its normal color."   SOURCES: CNNhttps://edition.cnn.com/2018/09/05/health/black-hairy-tongue-study/index.html***]]></description>
