      <title>Unique surgery allows cancer patient to dance again</title>
      <description><![CDATA[For story suggestions or custom animation requests, contact tips@nextanimation.com.tw. Visit http://archive.nextanimationstudio.com to view News Direct's complete archive of 3D news animations.RESTRICTIONS: Broadcast: NO USE JAPAN, NO USE TAIWAN Digital: NO USE JAPAN, NO USE TAIWANA young cancer survivor is still able to dance thanks to an innovative surgery. Delaney Unger, 12, was diagnosed with osteosarcoma of the left knee in 2016, which would require chemotherapy and amputation of her knee, according to CNN. Because of the location of her Unger's cancer, doctors were able to perform a rare procedure called a rotationplasty. During a 13-hour surgery in April of 2017, she had her left knee completely amputated. Surgeons then took Unger's ankle and foot, rotated them 180 degrees and attached them to the stump of her thigh, according to Newsday. This allowed her ankle to function as a knee. In October of 2017, Unger, who is now cancer free, received a prosthetic which fits over the backward-oriented foot and extends up the thigh. The prosthesis lets her walk, jump and dance.  RUNDOWN SHOWS:1. Location of osteosarcoma in Unger's left knee2. Unger receiving a rotationplasty3. Unger's ankle and foot being rotated 180 degrees then attached to her thigh4. Unger using her prosthetic leg to walk, jump and danceVOICEOVER (in English): "According to CNN, 12-year-old Delaney Unger was diagnosed with osteosarcoma of the left knee in 2016, which required chemotherapy and amputation of her knee."  "Because of the location of her Unger's cancer, doctors were able to perform a rare procedure called a rotationplasty. During a 13 hour surgery in April of 2017, she had her left knee completely amputated.""According to Newsday, surgeons then took Unger's ankle and foot, rotated them 180 degrees and attached them to the stump of her thigh. This allowed her ankle to function as a knee." "In October of 2017, Unger, who is now cancer-free, received a prosthetic which fits over the backward-oriented foot and extends up the thigh. The prosthesis lets her walk, jump and dance."  SOURCES: CNN, Newsdayhttps://edition.cnn.com/2018/09/10/health/cancer-survivor-backward-leg-dance/index.htmlhttps://www.newsday.com/news/health/ankle-knee-surgery-cancer-dancer-1.20932903***]]></description>
