      <description><![CDATA[For story suggestions or custom animation requests, contact tips@nextanimation.com.tw. Visit http://archive.nextanimationstudio.com to view News Direct's complete archive of 3D news animations.RESTRICTIONS: Broadcast: NO USE JAPAN, NO USE TAIWAN Digital: NO USE JAPAN, NO USE TAIWANWildlife officials in Utah have been restocking remote lakes in the mountain by dropping fish from airplanes, reports Live Science.On Twitter, wildlife officials explained the lakes are being stocked "to provide fishing opportunities for the public."Officials say the fish used are usually only about 3 centimeters to 7 centimeters long and are used to restock more than 200 lakes in the state every year.Officials claim about 95% of the fish are expected to survive the drop because of their small size.Previous methods included using milk cans to store the fish and loading it onto animals such as horses to reach remote areas, CNN reports.However, officials say they have been using this method since 1956 and claims it is less stressful on the fish than the previous method used. The previous method of transporting the fish by ground also reportedly took a lot longer than the current method. RUNDOWN SHOWS:1. Airplane is shown dropping fishes into lake.2. One tiny fish and lake is shown.3. A group of tiny fish is shown. 4. A milk can and a horse is shown.VOICEOVER (in English): "Live Science reports wildlife officials in Utah have been restocking remote lakes in the mountain by dropping fish from airplanes.""Officials say the fish used are usually only about 3 centimeters to 7 centimeters long and are used to restock more than 200 lakes in the state every year.""Officials claim about 95% of the fish are expected to survive the drop because of their small size.""According to CNN, previous methods included using milk cans to store the fish and loading it onto animals such as horses to reach remote areas."SOURCES: Live Science, Utah Division of Wildlife Resources, Fox News