      <title>Low-carb, keto diets may have negative long-term consequences</title>
      <description><![CDATA[For story suggestions or custom animation requests, contact tips@nextanimation.com.tw. Visit http://archive.nextanimationstudio.com to view News Direct's complete archive of 3D news animations.RESTRICTIONS: Broadcast: NO USE JAPAN, NO USE TAIWAN Digital: NO USE JAPAN, NO USE TAIWANNew studies have found that low-carb diets may not be healthy in the long run.Business Insider reports that the ketogenic diet is a high-fat, low carb plan where healthy fats make up 80% of a person's daily calories, and protein 20%. Only 50 grams of carbohydrates are allowed a day, compared to the USDA recommendation of 225 to 325 grams.The idea is to go into a state of ketosis, in which the body burns fat instead of carbohydrates for energy.But while a ketogenic diet helps reduce sugar and processed food intake, according to a study of overweight men published in the American Journal of Clinical Nutrition, it doesn't necessarily burn more body fat.Dieters tend to eliminate healthier carbohydrates like bananas, legumes, or oats, and with them nutrients like magnesium, calcium, and potassium. Some of the findings suggest going low-carb could lead to glucose intolerance or even diabetes, though more research is needed to confirm this.Research that looked at eating patterns of U.S. adults found that those who ate a moderate amount of carbs were more likely to live longer than high or low carb eaters.A third study that surveyed Europeans' eating habits revealed that those who ate fewer fresh vegetables, fruits, and nuts are more likely to develop deadly cancers.RUNDOWN SHOWS:1. Keto diet is high fat, low carb2. Carbs are limited to 50 grams with keto diet3. Body burns up glucose then turns fat into fatty acids when carbs are taken out of diet4. Keto diet doesn't burn more body fat than regular regime5. Low-carb diet eliminates healthy carbs, nutrients6. Moderate carb eaters live longer than high or low carb dieters7. People with diets of lower nutritional quality more likely to develop deadly cancersVOICEOVER (in English): "The ketogenic diet is a high-fat, low carb plan where healthy fats make up 80 percent of a person's daily calories, and protein 20 percent." "Only 50 grams of carbohydrates are allowed a day, compared to the USDA recommendation of 225 to 325 grams." "The idea is to go into a state of ketosis, in which the body burns fat instead of carbohydrates for energy." "But while a ketogenic diet helps reduce sugar and processed food intake, according to a laboratory testing of overweight men, it doesn't necessarily burn more body fat.""Dieters also tend to eliminate healthier carbohydrates like bananas, legumes, or oats, and with them nutrients like magnesium, calcium, and potassium.""Research that looked at eating patterns of U.S. adults found that those who ate a moderate amount of carbs were more likely to live longer than high or low carb eaters.""A third study that surveyed Europeans' eating habits revealed that those who ate fewer fresh vegetables, fruits, and nuts are more likely to develop deadly cancers."SOURCES: American Journal of Clinical Nutrition, PLOS Medicine, Business Insiderhttps://academic.oup.com/ajcn/article/104/2/324/4564649https://journals.plos.org/plosmedicine/article?id=10.1371/journal.pmed.1002651http://www.businessinsider.com/what-is-keto-diet-beginners-2017-12/#the-keto-diet-is-like-atkins-on-steroids-it-turns-the-body-into-a-fat-burning-machine-4https://www.businessinsider.com/low-carb-diets-linked-to-higher-risk-of-death-2018-8?utm_source=hearst&uthttps://www.businessinsider.com/amount-of-carbs-to-eat-for-a-long-life-2018-8?utm_source=hearst&utm_medium=referral&utm_content=allverticals***]]></description>
