      <description><![CDATA[For story suggestions or custom animation requests, contact tips@nextanimation.com.tw. Visit http://archive.nextanimationstudio.com to view News Direct's complete archive of 3D news animations.RESTRICTIONS: Broadcast: NO USE JAPAN, NO USE TAIWAN Digital: NO USE JAPAN, NO USE TAIWANA team of archaeologists have discovered an ancient shipwreck off the coast of Cascais, Portugal earlier this month, reports The Guardian.The ship was believed to be returning from a trip to India and was carrying different relics from the late 16th or early 17th century when it sank.The wreckage was discovered 12 meters beneath the surface of the water, covering an area 100 meters long and 50 meters wide.The director of the project said the wreckage was discovered by divers using geophysical survey equipment.Peppercorns, cowrie shells and nine bronze cannons were found at the site as well as fragments of Chinese porcelain dating back to the 16th and 17th century.The mayor of Cascais said the discovery is extraordinary and helps us learn more about history. Officials plan to examine the artifacts and believe there is still more to be discovered at the site.RUNDOWN SHOWS:1. The location of where the shipwreck was discovered is shown on a map.2. The wreckage is shown.3. Divers are shown locating the wreckage.4. Relics found at the site are shown.VOICEOVER (in English): "The Guardian reports a team of archaeologists have discovered an ancient shipwreck off the coast of Cascais, Portugal earlier this month.""The wreckage was discovered 12 meters beneath the surface of the water, covering an area 100 meters long and 50 meters wide.""The director of the project said the wreckage was discovered by divers using geophysical survey equipment.""Pepper corns, cowrie shells and nine bronze cannons were found at the site as well as fragments of Chinese porcelain dating back to the 16th and 17th century."SOURCES: Fox News, BBC News, Reuters, Newsweek, NPR, ABC News, http://www